The
treatment
of
salivary
fistulae

by
massage
and
hot
air

By
Dr.
P.
KOUINDJY,

Chef
du
Service
de
plivsiotliiirapit*
au
Val-de-Graee.

The
treatment
of
wounds
and
ulcers
by
massage
and
hot

air
is
no
new
thing.
Before
the
war,
de
Munter,
Lanel,
Daus-

set,
Bloch
and
others
had
published
works
on
the
usefulness

of
these
agents
in
the
treatment
of
varicose
ulcers
and
of
ulcers

which
had
proved
impossible
to
heal
by
any
other
means.
In

1905,
we
ourselves
reported
to
the
Societe
de
kinesitherapie

a
case
of
indolent
ulcer
cured
by
massage.
The
war
has

afforded
us
opportunities
of
demonstrating
that
fistulae
and

atonic
wounds
will
ultimately
heal
completely
when
subjected

to
massotherapy
and
a
hot
air
current
in
combination.
More-

over,
Dr.
Cyriax
of
London
has
quite
recently
established
a

method
of
treating
war
wounds
by
massage
only.
In
a
report

published
by
one
of
his
pupils,
Dr.
Louise
Bennet,
instances

are
cited
of
the
healing
of
freely
suppurating
wounds
invol-

ving
nerves
by
Cyriax's
method,
which
is
merely
a
modifica-

tion
of
the
general
method
of
Kellgren,
and
consists
chiefly
in

a
system
of
manual
vibrations.

We
have
applied
massotherapy
to
cicatrised
wounds
of
the

face
during
the
war,
and
have
had
many
occasions
of
proving

its
efficacity,
especially
when
used
in
combination
with
a
current

of
hot
air;
the
scars,
even
those
of
a
keloid
type,
become
softer

and
less
adherent,
they
lose
their
contractility,
and
can
be

detached
more
easily
from
the
deep
tissues;
with
the
result

that
correction
of
the
asymmetry
of
the
patient's
face
becomes

in
a
great
measure
possible.
